This is the fastest win because it proves value today.

Startup flow for AI Docs Writer

At app boot:

1. Fetch configs from config-hub


2. Store them in memory


3. Subscribe to live updates


4. Hot-reload without restart



Example (Rust client usage inside AI Docs Writer)

use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::{Arc, RwLock};

type ConfigMap = Arc<RwLock<HashMap<String, String>>>;

async fn load_initial_config(configs: ConfigMap) {
    let res = reqwest::get(
        "http://config-hub/configs/ai-docs-writer/prod"
    ).await.unwrap();

    let items: Vec<ConfigItem> = res.json().await.unwrap();

    let mut map = configs.write().unwrap();
    for item in items {
        map.insert(item.key, item.value);
    }
}

Then your app never reads env vars again:

let db_url = configs.read().unwrap().get("DATABASE_URL").unwrap();

This alone:

removes .env sprawl

removes redeploys

removes config drift


Thatâ€™s operational gravity disappearing.
